Clearly a very popular and established spot. Our server was very friendly and attentive. However, the food is mediocre at best and perhaps a bit overpriced. Tapas is about preparing great ingredients with simplicity. We felt like the ingredients used were basic and far from fresh. Gamba’s (quite small and completely peeled - not a good sign) were swimming in a very thick sauce, so were the mushrooms. Batatas bravas soggy and diced too finely. Empanadas had a tasty filling but  crust was way too thick - basically pie crust. Calamares Fritos were quite nice but missing the traditional aioli. Haven’t tried the paella, looked pretty good from afar. Steer clear if you’re expecting traditional tapas the likes of which they serve in Spain, but by all means give it a shot if you’re in for a drink and some comfort food.

OK, a few things: 1) The staff took excellent care of every single person in building. It started with my wife and I walked in the building. We were five minutes late for our reservation, but our table still wasn’t ready. Technically, they had a table ready, but when the host learned it was our 10th anniversary, that table was no longer good enough. They treated us to a much better setting in the restaurant. We never ran out of our drink, and there was always food on the table. And as far as we could tell, everyone was getting that exact same service.  2) The food. We ordered 5 tapas and they were so dang amazing. It was the best meal we had in NYC. By far. When we informed the server we are sober, he suggested a few house drinks that are non alcoholic and he was spot on. They were so tasty.  3) The price was on point. My wife and I spent a week in New York for our 10th anniversary. This was the best restaurant experience we had and it cost us the least amount of money. I would’ve paid double to have that same experience. I was surprised, honestly, when we got our check.

This is one of the best spots for lunch in the city, IMO! Firstly the service is amazingly good. Both at tables and while sitting at the bar service is prompt and gracious. They also have a happy hour and live music on the weekends.  And although it is CASH ONLY, there is an ATM on the premises.

We visited Manolo Tapas to celebrate my cousin's birthday. This place has a very nice decor, and it's very clean but it's a small location. As soon as you enter, to the right is there bar location with a few chairs. To the left is there main dinning room. They have an additional private seating area located in the basement, which accommodates about 18 people. The staff was very nice and professional. The server recommended the paella, which he said was there best dish. It didn't have the traditional saffron flavors that a paella has, but presentation was nice. I had the Rib-eye which was under cooked but they fixed that without an issue, but I wanted vegetables but my waiter informed me that it comes with french fries and the veggies is an additional cost. The food was already a little pricey to begin with, churrasco Steak is $34 and Rib-eye $38. I'm not sure if I would return to this location or recommend it, but everyone deserves a second chance.

I came here before a theater show. I will say that the service and food turnaround is really quick, without making you feel like they want you out of the restaurant as soon as possible. The wait staff was helpful in making recommendations and offering advice on food choices. This place is CASH ONLY. they have an ATM for you to use.  It's pretty spacious and has seating for larger groups, they also are portioned to let themselves out for private events if you choose. I do like the decor, lots of wood and they have some spanish themed pieces on the wall, looks like a little restaurant in spain as you travel the roads between cities.  While they have larger plates, we chose the hot tapas- we had  the dates, the chorizo in wine sauce, the shrimp and the steak on bread slices. I highly recommend the dates and the shrimp, the sauce for the latter was fantastic. The other dishes were great as well, they rounded out the meal, I would say everything was really flavorful and uniquely prepared. I also got the honey ice cream crepes for dessert which were delish and they come with preserves. total bill was $50

My friends and I come here all the time to get tapas and have a great time. The cocktail menu is a bit outdated, but the coconut margaritas are to die for.  You should definitely try their beer selection though. It's mostly, if not all, imported beer, and worth every penny.

Save yourself the headache and eat somewhere else. I came to Manolo Tapas to celebrate something special with a few friends and the beginning of our night was ruined. We had to find somewhere else to eat at the last minute because of our awful experience.  #1. CASH ONLY! In 2018 (almost 2019)!  #2. Very pretentious! There is a difference between having an upscale vibe to your restaurant and being downright obnoxious. Those employees must think they’re hot sh*t. A member of my party could not eat here due to the limited menu options and the waiter was unnecessarily rude to them. They treated them like they were beneath their restaurant only because they could not eat here. There’s actually a sign that tells outsiders to keep their voices down. THIS IS IN WASHINGTON HEIGHTS! Sidenote: Workers in uniform are allowed to smoke a cigarette outside, but people can’t wait a few minutes outside for their Uber?  #3. Extremely limited menu! If you look closely at the items, some of them are actually the same concept but with one little tweaked ingredient. Menu does not have side dishes, like rice or fries, only overpriced main courses.  #4. Speaking of main courses, portions are extremely small for the price.  This review will also be posted on Yelp.
